UI_visible_response: The "Jasmine Revolution" refers to the popular uprising in Tunisia that took place in 2011, which protested against corruption, poverty, and political repression under the regime of former dictator Zine el Abidine Ben Ali2. This revolution was marked by an intense campaign of civil resistance, including street demonstrations, and ultimately led to the toppling of Ben Ali's government3. The movement paved the way for a multi-party democracy in Tunisia, resulting in the release of political prisoners and greater political freedoms4. It also inspired similar movements across many Arabic countries, playing a significant role in the broader Arab Spring7.
